Lets import the data

This is based on the data that is stored and updated daily on this Git Repository https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19. Please clone this repo, and get the data locally, if you want to rerun this code.

Next, lets look at the data on the logarithmic scale. Apart from a few countries, like China, South Korea, Iran, and even Italy, all other countries seem to be very close to a straight line. Suggesting an almost perfect exponential growth in cases.

Given how good the exponential fit seems to be, I next perform a regression to predict the future number of cases by country. This is a very simple model, a country specific regression, where we fit a linear regression to the logarithm of the number of cases. In the absence of significant efforts, like the lockdowns that are currently in place, each of the countries below are likely to see million plus cases, in just 10 days.

Cases across all countries

Next, lets analyze the number of confirmed cases for all coutries. Again, I fit a simple model to capture the pattern. I fit a degree 3 polynomial to capture the pattern thus far, and extrapolate it for the next 15 days. Additionally, I add a weight that gives greater weights to later time points, the goal of this is to capture the possible effect of the significant worldwide social distancing efforts. Of course, this does not entirely capture the effect of the social distancing, especially what we will see in the coming days. But if nothing were done, this could be a very likely scenario. The scary thing with this fit is that the regression has an Adjusted R-squared of 0.9939, showing how good a fit this simple regression model is to the data.

Even Italy seems to be doing better. But at this rate, the US will have 10,000 deaths within 10 days.

Deaths across all countries

Next, lets analyze the deaths for all coutries. Again, I fit a simple model to capture the pattern. I fit a degree 3 polynomial to capture the pattern thus far, and extrapolate it for the next 15 days. Of course, this does not capture the effect of the social distancing efforts that are currently on-going all over the world. But if nothing were done, this could be a very likely scenario. The scary thing with this fit is that the regression has an Adjusted R-squared of 0.9986, showing how good a fit this simple regression model is to the data.

Are we over the peak?

Lets look at whether we are over the peak daily cases and deaths. Most countries seem to be past the peak in cases. But for the daily deaths, we see some countries that are past their peaks, but many are still rising.

Mortality Rate

Next, lets start looking at the mortality rates across countries. We see a big spread, going from 0.5% in Germany to 10% in Italy.

Lets also look at the mortality rate over time (the curves below are smoothed). We see that the mortality rate for most countries seem to be rising. There are two opposing forces:

  1. Force 1: The denominator is low, not all cases (especially the mild cases are not tested). If this is true, as testing rolls out extensively, we expect to see the mortality rate to fall.
  2. Force 2: The numerator is low, many people who die will likely pass away weeks or months from case confirmation. This means that the mortality rate will grow as time passes.

Lets look at a few cases below.

  • For Italy and Spain, the mortality rate seems to be rising steadily. This is discencerting because the rate is already very high for these counrties. The UK, France and The Netherlands seems to be displaying a very similar pattern. These seem to suggest that we are seeing Force 2 dominate Force 1. The other possibility is that the disease spread is such that the increased testing is not testing enough mild cases.
  • For the US, we see two distinct patterns, first the rate was going down, and then it is going up. Given the lack of testing in the US in the early days, it is likely that the it first went down as many mild cases were detected.
